From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: =?UTF-8?q?Florian=20H=C3=A4nel?= <florian.haenel@echtzeit.solutions>
Date: Sun, 5 Jul 2026 11:57:05 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 10/13] platform/x86: msi-wmi-platform: fix debugfs writes
 executing stale data
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The debugfs write handler runs the WMI method on the previous contents
of data->buffer and only then copies the just-written payload into it,
clobbering the method's result. Net effect: every write executes the
*previous* write's command (initially zeroes), and a subsequent read
shows the raw payload instead of the firmware's reply, so the debugfs
interface never exposes a result at all.

Copy the payload into the buffer first and run the method on it, under
a single critical section; the in/out buffer then holds the reply for
reading, matching the documented semantics (and the behaviour of the
mainline driver before the input-buffer rework in this series).

Signed-off-by: Florian Hänel <florian.haenel@echtzeit.solutions>
Assisted-by: Claude:claude-fable-5
---
 drivers/platform/x86/msi-wmi-platform.c | 5 +----
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 4 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/platform/x86/msi-wmi-platform.c b/drivers/platform/x86/msi-wmi-platform.c
index f2dc564..d477ded 100644
--- a/drivers/platform/x86/msi-wmi-platform.c
+++ b/drivers/platform/x86/msi-wmi-platform.c
@@ -1402,6 +1402,7 @@ static ssize_t msi_wmi_platform_debugfs_write(struct file *fp, const char __user
 		return ret;
 
 	down_write(&data->buffer_lock);
+	memcpy(data->buffer, payload, data->length);
 	ret = msi_wmi_platform_query(data->data, data->method, data->buffer,
 				     data->length);
 	up_write(&data->buffer_lock);
@@ -1409,10 +1410,6 @@ static ssize_t msi_wmi_platform_debugfs_write(struct file *fp, const char __user
 	if (ret < 0)
 		return ret;
 
-	down_write(&data->buffer_lock);
-	memcpy(data->buffer, payload, data->length);
-	up_write(&data->buffer_lock);
-
 	return length;
 }
 
